        theory(1, "Our Environment",
            "Identify four sources of energy that can be used in Ghana efficiently and affordably.\nDescribe four ways of conserving energy in a household and classroom setting.\nList two examples each of renewable and non-renewable energy resources.",
            "(a) Four sources of energy that can be used efficiently and affordably in Ghana:\n1. Solar Energy: Abundant, clean, and free sunlight can be harvested using solar panels.\n2. Hydroelectric Power: Generating electricity from flowing river water (e.g. Akosombo, Bui dams).\n3. Liquified Petroleum Gas (LPG): Clean-burning gas used for domestic cooking instead of wood/charcoal.\n4. Biogas: Sourced from decaying organic agricultural waste and sewage, useful for local heating and power.\n\n(b) Four ways of conserving energy:\n1. Switch Off Lights: Turning off bulbs, fans, and ACs when leaving unoccupied classrooms or bedrooms.\n2. Use Energy-Efficient Bulbs: Replacing power-hungry incandescent bulbs with low-consumption LED light bulbs.\n3. Unplug Appliances: Unplugging chargers, televisions, and electronics from the wall when not in use to stop standby power draw.\n4. Natural Lighting/Ventilation: Opening windows and curtains during the day to use natural sunlight and cool breezes instead of artificial bulbs and fans.\n\n(c) Examples of energy resources:\n- Renewable energy: Solar power, wind energy, tidal energy, hydroelectric power.\n- Non-renewable energy: Crude oil (petroleum), natural gas, coal, uranium.",
            "4 Energy sources: 4 Marks\n4 Energy conservation methods: 12 Marks\nRenewable/Non-renewable examples: 4 Marks\nTotal: 20 Marks", 20),

