            "(a) Four republican constitutions of Ghana:\n1. The First Republican Constitution of 1960.\n2. The Second Republican Constitution of 1969.\n3. The Third Republican Constitution of 1979.\n4. The Fourth Republican Constitution of 1992.\n\n(b) Four ways a foreign national can acquire Ghanaian citizenship:\n1. Citizenship by Registration (Marriage): A foreigner who marries a Ghanaian citizen can legally register to become a citizen.\n2. Citizenship by Naturalization: A foreigner who resides in Ghana continuously for a long period (e.g. 10+ years) and meets legal character requirements can apply to naturalize.\n3. Citizenship by Adoption: A foreign child under the age of 16 who is legally adopted by Ghanaian parents automatically becomes a citizen.\n4. Presidential/Special Honour: The President can confer honorary citizenship on foreign individuals for outstanding contributions to the nation.\n\n(c) Explanation of Democracy:\nDemocracy is a system of governance where supreme political power is vested in the citizens. In a democracy, the citizens exercise this power either directly or through representatives they freely elect in scheduled, transparent, and fair public elections. It promotes the rule of law, protection of rights, and freedom of expression.",
            "4 Republican Constitutions: 4 Marks\n4 Citizenship pathways: 12 Marks\nDemocracy explanation: 4 Marks\nTotal: 20 Marks", 20),

